<TITLE> 4 Bangladeshis die on Hajj </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 2 (bdnews24.com)  Four Bangladeshi pilgrims have died performing Hajj in Saudi Arabia, officials said Sunday. "The four pilgrims, including two women, died of heart failure while undergoing treatment in hospital," Hajj officer Bazlul Haque Biswas told bdnews24.com. Biswas said one died in Jeddah, one at Medina and two in Makkah. The Bangladesh government's Hajj website (hajj.gov.bd) said Aleya Begum (Passport No C 1468667), of Rajoir in Madaripur, died at Al-Nur Hospital in Makkah on Sunday. She made private arrangements to perform Hajj through Eidgah Travels. Sikandar Ali (Passport No C 1088601), of Ranishankail in Thakurgaon, who went to Saudi Arabia under government management, died at Al-Ansar Hospital in Medina on Sunday. Moghul Ahsan (Passport No C 1669561), of Lalbagh in Dhaka, died at King Faisal Hospital in Makkah on Saturday. Osimuddin Shah (passport number not given), of Bogra, died at King Fahad Hospital in Jeddah on Oct 22 and was buried at a local graveyard on Oct 30. Biswas said the other three would also be buried in Saudi Arabia Hajj flights to Saudi Arabia began on Oct 21. A total of 58,634 Bangladeshis applied to perform Haj this year, of which 8,043 are under government management and the rest under private management. Among them, Biman Bangladesh Airlines and Saudi Arabian Airlines will carry 38,634 and 20,000 pilgrims respectively. b
